This paper is primarily focused on language modeling, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses scaling up LM using modern training methods, which involves optimization and machine learning techniques, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper addresses memory and communication bottlenecks, which are common issues in distributed computing, making cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) a possible sub-category. The paper also proposes a method for grouping parameters for common words and character sequences, which involves data structures and algorithms, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses empirical results to demonstrate the effectiveness of their proposed method, which involves experimentation and evaluation, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category.
